  <section>
    <h2>Effect of socioeconomic controls</h2>
    <p>According to BRÅ's methodology notes, statistically controlling for age, sex, socioeconomic status, and residential area substantially reduces the gap between immigrant-background and native-born suspect rates. A residual gap remains after full adjustment.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Age composition: immigrant populations have a higher share of young adults (the age group with the highest crime rates across all populations)</li>
      <li>Sex ratio: a higher male proportion in immigrant cohorts affects raw figures</li>
      <li>Socioeconomic status: concentration in low-income, high-unemployment areas is the largest explanatory variable</li>
      <li>Residential area: concentration in urban and high-poverty districts</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Methodological limits</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Uncontrolled confounders:</strong> Comparisons that do not fully control for socioeconomic status, urban density, and age produce inflated apparent differences.</li>
      <li><strong>Data discontinuity:</strong> BRÅ has not published this type of report since 2005. Systematic current statistics do not exist, making time-series comparisons impossible.</li>
      <li><strong>Suspects vs. convictions:</strong> Suspect rates measure police activity and investigation, not convictions. Local policing intensity and enforcement patterns may affect who is counted as a suspect.</li>
      <li><strong>Heterogeneity of offences:</strong> An index combining all crime types mixes minor infractions with serious offences.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this data does not show</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>National or ethnic origin does not cause crime. The correlation is largely explained by the socioeconomic conditions in which many immigrants find themselves (poverty, unemployment, social exclusion).</li>
      <li>The residual gap that persists after adjustment cannot be attributed to specific causes using available data. "Culture," "genetics," or "religion" are not operationalised as variables and cannot be invoked as explanations.</li>
      <li>Swedish statistics reflect Sweden's specific context (scale of refugee intake, integration policies). Direct extrapolation to other countries is unjustified.</li>
      <li>Because the data ends in 2005, current trends are unknown. Extrapolation from outdated data lacks evidential basis.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Primary source</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Brottsförebyggande rådet / BRÅ (2021). <em>Invandrares och invandrares avkomlingars representation i brottsstatistiken</em>. Rapport 2021:1. <a href="https://www.bra.se" rel="noopener">www.bra.se</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>
